07320nam a22009375i 9786155053597DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222012hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97861550535977 a10.1515/97861550535972doi  a(DE-B1597)633231  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aHQ638b.A53 2012eb 7aHIS0540002bisacsh04a306.85094722304aAnd They Lived Happily Ever After :bNorms and Everyday Practices of Family and Parenthood in Russia and Eastern Europe /ced. by Helene Carlback, Zhanna Kravchenko, Yulia Gradskova. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (338 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. 1940s–1980s THE FAMILY AS A “BASIC UNIT OF SOCIALIST SOCIETY” -- tCHAPTER 1 Lone Motherhood in Soviet Russia in the Mid-20th Century—In a European Context -- tChapter 2. Family, Divorce, and Comrades’ Courts: Soviet Family and Public Organizations During the Thaw -- tChapter 3. A Life of Labor, a Life of Love: Telling the Life of a Young Peasant Mother Facing Collectivization -- tChapter 4. East German Women Going West: Family, Children and Partners in Life-Experience Literature -- tChapter 5. Why Does Public Policy Implementation Fail? Lithuanian Office of State Benefits for Mothers of Large Families and Single Mothers, 1944–1956 -- tChapter 6. The Latvian Family Experience with Sovietization 1945–1990 -- tPART II 1990s–2000s SOCIAL TRANSFORMATION IN THE MIRROR OF FAMILY LIFE -- tChapter 7. “Two children Puts You in the Zone of Social Misery:” Childbearing and Risk Perception among Russian Women -- tChapter 8. “Supporting Genuine Development of the Child:” Public Childcare Centers Versus Family in Post-Soviet Russia -- tChapter 9. Everyday Continuity and Change: Family and Family Policy in Russia -- tChapter 10. Single Mothers—Clients or Citizens? Social Work with Poor Families in Russia -- tChapter 11. Welfare Crisis and Crisis Centers in Russia Today -- tChapter 12. Marriage and Divorce Law in Russia and the Baltic States: Overview of Recent Changes -- tChapter 13. Doing Parenting in Post-Socialist Estonia and Latvia -- tChapter 14. Gendered Experiences in Entrepreneurship, Family and Social Activities in Russia -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTakes a comparative perspective on family life and childhood in the past half century in Russia and Eastern Europe, highlighting similarities and differences. Focuses on the problematic domains of the institutions and laws devised to cope with family difficulties, and discusses the social strains created by the transition from communist to post-communist national systems. In addition to the substantial historic analysis, actual challenges are also discussed. The essays examine the changing gender roles, alterations in legal systems, the burdens faced by married and unmarried women who are mothers, the contrasts between government rhteoric and the implementation of policies toward marriage, children and parenthood. By addressing the specifics of welfare politics under the Communist rule and the directions of their transformation in 1990–2000s, this book contributes to the understanding of social institutions and family policies in these countries and the problems of dealing with the socialist past that this region face.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aFamilieszBaltic States. 0aFamilieszEurope, Eastern. 0aFamilieszRussia (Federation). 0aFamilieszSoviet Union. 0aFamily policyzBaltic States. 0aFamily policyzRussia (Federation). 0aFamily policyzSoviet Union. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aCollectivization, Communism, Family life, Women, Judiciary, Peasants, Postcommunism, Social policy.1 aAsztalos Morell, Ildikó, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlback, Helene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarlbäck, Helene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarhan, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGradskova, Yulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGradskova, Yulia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIarskaia-Smirnova, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKesseli, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhazova, Olga A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKravchenko, Zhanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKravchenko, Zhanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeinarte, Dalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunicio-Larsson, Ingegerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomanov, Pavel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRotkirch, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuncis, Maija, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaarinen, Aino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSätre, Ann-Mari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZhidkova, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978615505359740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155053597423Coveruhttps://www.